{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013ufrwrPV7bA6vxQPz1WL1r","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The log files are owned by `filebeat` user, not the elasticsearch user. The log directory has write permissions for everyone (`drwxrwxrwx`). But there's no JSON log file - only GC log files. \n\nThis is because the ES 8.11.1 Docker image by default writes JSON logs to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs/es-cluster.log` and similar. But we're mounting the emptyDir at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs`, and the ES container hasn't written its JSON logs yet to the shared volume.\n\nWait, actually - the files are owned by `filebeat` user which is suspicious. \n\nActually, those GC logs (`gc.log`, `gc.log.00`, `gc.log.01`) are coming from the JVM inside Elasticsearch, and the ownership might be showing as filebeat because both containers are running as root in my patch. I need to check what user the ES container actually runs as in the original spec.\n\nThe Elasticsearch 8.x image defaults to running as the `elasticsearch` user (uid 1000), so when it writes those GC logs to the emptyDir, they're created with that uid. But since the filebeat container is running as root, it can read them regardless, and the display might show them mapped to the filebeat user depending on how the container's user namespace is configured.\n\nThe real problem is that filebeat is trying to parse GC log files as JSON, but they're plain text. The actual JSON logs from Elasticsearch 8.11.1 — like the main cluster log and slowlog — haven't appeared in the shared volume yet, which suggests either they're being written to a different location or haven't been generated during startup.\n\nI need to reconfigure filebeat to handle these separately: GC logs should skip JSON parsing entirely, while the JSON logs get the proper ndjson parser when they do appear.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_detai