{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CWhXTpnQ9BZwMDB3u7XJGv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to restart the filebeat containers on the pods to pick up the new config. ConfigMaps are updated dynamically in Kubernetes (mounted volumes are updated within ~1-2 minutes), but the filebeat process won't pick up the new config without a restart.\n\nI can either:\n1. Do a rolling restart of the StatefulSet (`kubectl rollout restart`)\n2. Delete the individual pods to force a restart\n\nBut wait - rolling restart will trigger the ES container to restart too, which might be disruptive. However, since the ES container also gets restarted (all containers in a pod restart together when the pod restarts), this could disrupt the ES cluster.\nActually, the best approach is to use `kubectl rollout restart statefulset/elasticsearch -n elasticsearch`. This will do a rolling restart,  restarting one pod at a time and waiting for each to be ready before moving to the next, which keeps the cluster healthy throughout. I can't restart just the filebeat container without restarting the whole pod, and filebeat doesn't hot-reload config anyway, so a full pod restart is necessary.\n\nBefore I proceed with the rolling restart, I should verify that the ES cluster is configured with shard replication and can handle rolling restarts gracefully.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3562,"cache_read_input_tokens":70479,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3562},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3c254387-153b-4876-b104-fac31aa7be5d","uuid":"2ce536fc-c943-42aa-b0c2-d6343a78777f","request_id":"req_011CcPHbVqwWYpUGnp8qxV5L"}
